sdp/logs/Verify_T-021_20260416T043834Z_1776337553.log:3876:./sdp/logs/Verify_T-006_20260416T043834Z_1776330893.log:1961:sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4445:sdp/templates/candidates/lead_t2/v001.md:80:- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Add bootstrap_identity() invocation in startup flow (before FirstBootAnnouncer) so first boots mint and persist identity automatically..
sdp/logs/Verify_T-021_20260416T043834Z_1776337553.log:3877:./sdp/logs/Verify_T-006_20260416T043834Z_1776330893.log:1962:sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4447:sdp/templates/candidates/verify/v001.md:94:- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Add bootstrap_identity() invocation in startup flow (before FirstBootAnnouncer) so first boots mint and persist identity automatically..
sdp/logs/Verify_T-021_20260416T043834Z_1776337553.log:3878:./sdp/logs/Verify_T-006_20260416T043834Z_1776330893.log:1963:sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4451:I spotted one design-gap concern: `bootstrap_identity()` is now called on startup, but the call is unparameterized (`mode` defaults to `standalone`), so first boot identity mode depends on pre-existing file; if this startup path were first-run federated, identity would not be minted as federated unless caller writes file ahead of time. I’ll include this in the verification notes.
sdp/logs/Verify_T-021_20260416T043834Z_1776337553.log:3879:./sdp/logs/Verify_T-006_20260416T043834Z_1776330893.log:1964:sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4470:No new security exposure is introduced. Identity persistence behavior is covered by existing `bootstrap_identity` tests, and startup wiring invokes `bootstrap_identity` before first-boot announcement. Identity handling remains file-based and append-only at startup.
sdp/logs/Verify_T-021_20260416T043834Z_1776337553.log:3880:./sdp/logs/Verify_T-006_20260416T043834Z_1776330893.log:1965:sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4477:- [ ] Startup identity bootstrap occurs before `FirstBootAnnouncer` in daemon, but `bootstrap_identity()` is called with default arguments and does not explicitly set mode for federated first-boot scenarios. This can mint standalone identity unless an identity file already exists. Severity: minor
sdp/logs/Verify_T-021_20260416T043834Z_1776337553.log:3881:./sdp/logs/Verify_T-006_20260416T043834Z_1776330893.log:1966:sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4483:- If federated and standalone startup are both supported, pass an explicit mode into `bootstrap_identity()` when entering those startup flows; keep the recurring hardening check for identity persistence between boots.
sdp/logs/Verify_T-021_20260416T043834Z_1776337553.log:3882:./sdp/logs/Verify_T-006_20260416T043834Z_1776330893.log:1967:sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4514:No new security exposure is introduced. Identity persistence behavior is covered by existing `bootstrap_identity` tests, and startup wiring invokes `bootstrap_identity` before first-boot announcement. Identity handling remains file-based and append-only at startup.
